OL,24,ANext PageBS-SE Eng NewsCThis DayFReg TV
FL,383,380,120,260,000,100
PN,38202
SC,0002
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F382A1784638109
OL,3,CRare Titanic letter written days
OL,4,Cbefore sinking to go under the hammer
OL,6,FHe was travelling to Boston to visit
OL,7,Frelatives and the letter, dated April
OL,8,F10, was postmarked Queenstown.
OL,10,FThe letter speaks of the fine weather
OL,11,Fand the good atmosphere on the ship.
OL,13,FThe historic item is going under the
OL,14,Fhammer at Henry Aldridge and Son of
OL,15,FDevizes, Wiltshire, on Sunday.
OL,17,FMr Hodges wrote: "Dear Hector,
OL,26,@yD@ROU
OL,1,W~s1x0~s1~s hw1~k4~c1 hw}h7}j7}   G2/6
OL,2,W,.!" ,.!+, "-$/*%+.!+,*%/*%/*-'T(,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext PageBS-SE Eng NewsCThis DayFReg TV
FL,383,380,120,260,000,100
PN,38203
SC,0003
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F382A1784638109
OL,3,CRare Titanic letter written days
OL,4,Cbefore sinking to go under the hammer
OL,6,F"Very many thanks for the telegram and
OL,7,Ffor the good wishes. It was a kind and
OL,8,Fthoughtful act and much appreciated,
OL,9,Fand you will please convey my thanks
OL,10,Fto the members of our Association.
OL,12,F"Wasn't it good of the President to
OL,13,Fcome and see me off? I almost believe
OL,14,FI could have persuaded him to come
OL,15,Falong. We have had a fine time up to
OL,16,Fnow.
OL,18,F"You do not see anything of the
OL,19,Fmovement of the ship, but the weather
OL,20,Fis very fine.
OL,26,@nD@AOUtD@AOUzD@AOU
OL,1,W~s1x0~s1~s hw1~k4~c1 hw}h7}j7}   G3/6
OL,2,W,.!" ,.!+, "-$/*%+.!+,*%/*%/*-'T(,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext PageBS-SE Eng NewsCThis DayFReg TV
FL,383,380,120,260,000,100
PN,38204
SC,0004
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F382A1784638109
OL,3,CRare Titanic letter written days
OL,4,Cbefore sinking to go under the hammer
OL,6,F"On the top deck there are about 200
OL,7,Fboys (from 20 upwards) marching round
OL,8,F& singing, others are playing dominoes
OL,9,F& cards in the saloons, some reading,
OL,10,Fsome writing, everything is quite
OL,11,Fdifferent to what you would expect to
OL,12,Fsee at sea.
OL,14,F"Tell your Dad I am very disappointed
OL,15,Fhe did not come, but I know he could
OL,16,Fnot help it, and it was more than
OL,17,Fexpected by your brother coming
OL,18,Finstead. (All for this but not him) I
OL,19,Fam going to bed early, for I feel as
OL,20,Ftired as a dead dog.
OL,26,@nD@AOUvD@AOU
OL,1,W~s1x0~s1~s hw1~k4~c1 hw}h7}j7}   G4/6
OL,2,W,.!" ,.!+, "-$/*%+.!+,*%/*%/*-'T(,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext PageBS-SE Eng NewsCThis DayFReg TV
FL,383,380,120,260,000,100
PN,38205
SC,0005
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F382A1784638109
OL,3,CRare Titanic letter written days
OL,4,Cbefore sinking to go under the hammer
OL,6,F"Good bye Hector
OL,8,F"Best wishes
OL,10,F"From Yours faithfully
OL,12,F"H.P. Hodges."
OL,14,FHe died in the sinking on April 15
OL,15,F1912, a tragedy that claimed 1,500
OL,16,Flives, and his body was later
OL,17,Frecovered and buried in Fairview
OL,18,FCemetery, Halifax, Nova Scotia.
OL,26,@nD@AOUpD@AOUrD@AOUtD@AOUtD@NO]
OL,1,W~s1x0~s1~s hw1~k4~c1 hw}h7}j7}   G5/6
OL,2,W,.!" ,.!+, "-$/*%+.!+,*%/*%/*-'T(,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext PageBS-SE Eng NewsCThis DayFReg TV
FL,383,380,120,260,000,100
PN,38206
SC,0006
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F382A1784638109
OL,3,CRare Titanic letter written days
OL,4,Cbefore sinking to go under the hammer
OL,6,FAuctioneer Andrew Aldridge said
OL,7,Fletters written by second-class
OL,8,Fpassengers are some of the rarest.
OL,10,F"This letter gives us a historically
OL,11,Fpriceless snapshot into what life was
OL,12,Flike onboard the most famous ship ever
OL,13,Fto take to the seas for a second class
OL,14,Fpassenger," he said.
OL,16,F"He describes the ship and fellow
OL,17,Fpassengers and how they passed the
OL,18,Ftime. Yet a little over four days
OL,19,Flater the Titanic was lying at the
OL,20,Fbottom of the North Atlantic."
OL,26,@rD@AOUvD@KO]xD@AOU|D@^O]
OL,1,W~s1x0~s1~s hw1~k4~c1 hw}h7}j7}   G6/6
